## Which topics matter most for FAANG interviews

Not all 454 problems carry equal weight. Interview frequency data from 2024-2025 reveals a clear hierarchy, and the A2Z sheet's heaviest sections align well with what FAANG companies actually ask.

**Tier 1 — The Big Four (~50% of FAANG questions):** Arrays (Step 3, 40 problems), Dynamic Programming (Step 16, 56 problems), Graphs (Step 15, 53 problems), and Binary Trees + BSTs (Steps 13-14, 55 problems combined). These four topic clusters total **204 problems — 45% of the sheet** — and dominate real interviews at Google, Meta, Amazon, Apple, and Netflix. DP is Amazon's favorite; Graphs are Google's and Meta's bread and butter; Trees appear everywhere.

**Tier 2 — High ROI (~30% of interview questions):** Binary Search (Step 4, 32 problems) appears far more often than beginners expect — "binary search on answers" is a recurring FAANG pattern. Sliding Window & Two Pointer (Step 10, 12 problems) delivers outsized interview value relative to its small size. Stacks & Queues (Step 9, 30 problems) — especially **monotonic stack problems** — are a favorite at Amazon and Microsoft. Linked Lists (Step 6, 31 problems) round out this tier.

**Tier 3 — Important but less frequent:** Recursion & Backtracking (Step 7), Greedy Algorithms (Step 12), Heaps (Step 11), and Tries (Step 17) collectively appear in roughly 15-20% of interviews. Backtracking problems like N-Queens and Sudoku Solver remain popular. Heaps show up for "Top K" and "Median from Stream" patterns.

**Tier 4 — Foundational, can speed through:** Basics (Step 1), Sorting (Step 2), Bit Manipulation (Step 8), and basic Strings (Step 5). Essential knowledge but rarely the focus of an interview question. Skip Step 1 entirely if you already know a programming language.

