## Difficulty distribution across topics tells you where to slow down

The sheet's 29/41/30 split (Easy/Medium/Hard) isn't uniform across steps. Understanding where difficulty concentrates helps you budget time.

**Steps with the highest Hard-problem density:** Graphs (Step 15) and DP (Step 16) have the most hard problems — roughly 40-50% of their problems qualify as Hard. Binary Trees (Step 13) and Arrays Hard (Step 3 Lec 3) follow. These four sections demand the most time per problem and are where candidates most often stall.

**Steps that are fastest to complete:** Sorting (Step 2, 7 problems), Sliding Window (Step 10, 12 problems), and Tries (Step 17, 7 problems) are compact. Don't let their small size fool you — Sliding Window and Tries are high-frequency interview topics relative to problem count.

**The "Easy-heavy" front-loading is intentional.** Steps 1-5 contain most of the Easy problems, building confidence and pattern recognition before Medium and Hard problems dominate Steps 6-18. The roadmap above respects this design.

