## Conclusion

The roadmap above compresses 454 problems into 12 working weeks plus one revision week, averaging **~5 problems daily at 3-4 hours of focused practice**. Three non-obvious insights from this analysis: First, completing even 80% of the sheet with deep understanding outperforms rushing through 100% — if time runs short, deprioritize Bit Manipulation (Step 8) and Advanced Strings (Step 18) before cutting anything from Trees, Graphs, or DP. Second, the real bottleneck isn't problem count but **pattern transfer** — the 10 core patterns (Two Pointers, Sliding Window, Binary Search, DFS/BFS, DP, Backtracking, Merge Intervals, Monotonic Stack, Union-Find, Heap) cover ~80% of what FAANG interviews test. Third, Week 7's recursion work on subsequence patterns is the single highest-leverage week in the entire plan, because it directly unlocks DP — the largest and hardest section. Invest extra time there, and DP in Weeks 12-13 becomes dramatically more manageable.
